1
00:00:59,726 --> 00:01:01,761
PRESIDENT BARACK OBAMA:
We have a supply of natural gas

2
00:01:01,795 --> 00:01:05,065
that can last America
nearly 100 years...

3
00:01:05,098 --> 00:01:06,533
[APPLAUSE]

4
00:01:06,566 --> 00:01:09,002
And my administration will take
every possible action

5
00:01:09,035 --> 00:01:10,837
to safely develop this energy.

6
00:01:10,870 --> 00:01:12,872
The development of natural gas
will create jobs

7
00:01:12,906 --> 00:01:16,476
and power trucks and factories
that are cleaner and cheaper,

8
00:01:16,509 --> 00:01:19,446
where we develop a hundred-year
supply of natural gas

9
00:01:19,479 --> 00:01:21,781
that's right beneath our feet.

10
00:01:23,383 --> 00:01:25,718
BILL CLINTON: The boom
in oil and gas production

11
00:01:25,752 --> 00:01:29,022
has driven oil imports
to a near-20-year low

12
00:01:29,055 --> 00:01:31,524
and natural gas production
to an all-time high.

13
00:01:31,558 --> 00:01:35,795
HILARY CLINTON: The United States
will promote the use of shale gas.

14
00:01:35,829 --> 00:01:40,033
Now I know that, in some places,
is controversial.

15
00:01:41,367 --> 00:01:44,037
PAUL RYAN: With 21st-century
drilling technology,

16
00:01:44,070 --> 00:01:47,540
you can get it out of the ground
in a very safe and secure way.

17
00:01:50,376 --> 00:01:53,880
MITT ROMNEY: I don't recall hearing
about water being on fire.

18
00:01:53,913 --> 00:01:55,849
We will have
North American energy.

19
00:01:55,882 --> 00:01:57,650
We're going to be independent.

20
00:01:57,684 --> 00:01:59,452
Thank you.
Thank you very much.

21
00:01:59,486 --> 00:02:00,453
Thank you very much.

22
00:02:00,487 --> 00:02:01,588
Thank you, God bless you,

23
00:02:01,621 --> 00:02:04,290
and God bless
the United States of America.

24
00:02:22,142 --> 00:02:24,144
MAN, VOICE-OVER: Hi.

25
00:02:24,177 --> 00:02:25,778
♪

26
00:02:25,812 --> 00:02:28,548
My name is Josh Fox.

27
00:02:28,581 --> 00:02:31,017
This is my house.

28
00:02:31,050 --> 00:02:35,021
It's in the middle of the woods,
tucked away on a dirt road

29
00:02:35,054 --> 00:02:37,557
in a small town next
to the Delaware River

30
00:02:37,590 --> 00:02:40,527
called Milanville, Pennsylvania.

31
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:43,563
Just past my backyard,
there's a stream

32
00:02:43,596 --> 00:02:45,565
that feeds the Delaware.

33
00:02:45,598 --> 00:02:47,600
It's been 5 years
since the first proposal

34
00:02:47,634 --> 00:02:51,638
to drill thousands of gas wells
in the Delaware River Basin

35
00:02:51,671 --> 00:02:54,140
came knocking at my door.

36
00:02:54,174 --> 00:02:56,776
Every day you wake up with it...

37
00:02:56,809 --> 00:02:58,811
the fate of my backyard,

38
00:02:58,845 --> 00:03:01,748
the watershed for millions
of people...

39
00:03:01,781 --> 00:03:04,384
up in the air.

40
00:03:10,757 --> 00:03:12,725
Sometimes, you can't figure out

41
00:03:12,759 --> 00:03:15,228
what's going on
in your own backyard

42
00:03:15,261 --> 00:03:17,897
without figuring out all
the places around the world

43
00:03:17,931 --> 00:03:21,067
that your backyard's
connected to.

44
00:03:26,506 --> 00:03:29,342
And, as we know, in sequels,

45
00:03:29,375 --> 00:03:32,345
the Empire strikes back.

46
00:03:32,378 --> 00:03:35,882
So let's start where
we left off...

47
00:03:35,915 --> 00:03:38,251
when the tide came in.

48
00:03:38,284 --> 00:03:41,921
♪

49
00:05:10,877 --> 00:05:13,246
It was hard to believe my eyes.

50
00:05:13,279 --> 00:05:15,715
As far as I could see,

51
00:05:15,748 --> 00:05:18,184
the surface of the Gulf,

52
00:05:18,217 --> 00:05:22,655
streaked with oil like ghosts
along the surface.

53
00:05:22,689 --> 00:05:25,224
Nothing could really
prepare you.

54
00:05:25,258 --> 00:05:28,728
We hadn't seen pictures
like this on the news.

55
00:05:28,761 --> 00:05:32,131
It had been widely reported
that journalists' flights

56
00:05:32,165 --> 00:05:35,568
were restricted
to 3,000 feet and above.

57
00:05:35,601 --> 00:05:38,705
Journalists would call up
the FAA to clear their flights,

58
00:05:38,738 --> 00:05:41,574
and BP would answer the phone.

59
00:05:41,607 --> 00:05:44,577
And I don't know why.
Maybe because it was a Sunday.

60
00:05:44,610 --> 00:05:48,581
Maybe because it was the Fourth
of July, and everybody was off.

61
00:05:48,614 --> 00:05:53,086
But somehow, we got clearance to
fly at any altitude we wanted,

62
00:05:53,119 --> 00:05:56,189
so this is what
it really looked like.

63
00:05:56,222 --> 00:05:59,892
♪

64
00:06:03,996 --> 00:06:06,499
Down on the ground,
we weren't so lucky...

65
00:06:06,532 --> 00:06:08,668
limited access to beaches...

66
00:06:08,701 --> 00:06:11,771
but we weren't the only ones
hitting roadblocks.

67
00:06:15,141 --> 00:06:17,243
I was getting
pretty good at this.

68
00:06:17,276 --> 00:06:19,746
You don't really have time
to sit back

69
00:06:19,779 --> 00:06:21,848
and say, "Why the hell
is this happening?"

70
00:06:21,881 --> 00:06:24,817
Why is BP...

71
00:06:24,851 --> 00:06:27,887
Are they in the back pocket?
They got a cozy deal?

72
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:31,424
Is their lobbyist in Washington
controlling this?

73
00:06:31,457 --> 00:06:33,793
But, um, something stinks.

74
00:06:33,826 --> 00:06:36,829
We're fighting harder with
the Coast Guard and BP

75
00:06:36,863 --> 00:06:39,165
than we're fighting the oil.

76
00:06:39,198 --> 00:06:43,669
I don't even want to start
to imagine things that...

77
00:06:43,703 --> 00:06:47,774
Why would this be?
Why would they be protected?

78
00:06:47,807 --> 00:06:50,343
FOX, VOICE-OVER: We found out
that BP was spraying chemical dispersants

79
00:06:50,376 --> 00:06:52,812
on surfaces of the Gulf
in huge volumes.

80
00:06:52,845 --> 00:06:55,047
A chemical that had been
banned in Britain

81
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:57,150
actually makes the oil
more toxic

82
00:06:57,183 --> 00:06:59,118
and sinks it out of sight.

83
00:06:59,152 --> 00:07:02,021
They weren't solving
the crisis, just hiding it.

84
00:07:02,054 --> 00:07:04,023
It's going to be ugly
if we quit spraying dispersant.

85
00:07:04,056 --> 00:07:06,659
It's going to be black oil
all over the surface.

86
00:07:06,692 --> 00:07:09,562
But this monster that continues
to grow every day,

87
00:07:09,595 --> 00:07:11,030
at least it's not invisible.

88
00:07:11,063 --> 00:07:14,901
Right now, they're making it
invisible, impossible to fight.

89
00:07:14,934 --> 00:07:19,439
For every decision they've made
throughout the catastrophe,

90
00:07:19,472 --> 00:07:22,909
there's been huge negative
impacts, and we...

91
00:07:22,942 --> 00:07:25,411
the people of Louisiana,
Mississippi,

92
00:07:25,445 --> 00:07:27,947
Alabama, and Florida...
are going to have to deal

93
00:07:27,980 --> 00:07:31,417
with those negative impacts
for a very, very long time.

94
00:07:31,451 --> 00:07:32,852
FOX: Years? Decades?

95
00:07:32,885 --> 00:07:35,354
SUBRA: Decades,
decades. Generations.

96
00:07:35,388 --> 00:07:37,857
And that's what is
so devastating

97
00:07:37,890 --> 00:07:39,725
to the fishing communities.

98
00:07:39,759 --> 00:07:42,061
FOX: So all the dispersant
does is it makes the oil sink?

99
00:07:42,094 --> 00:07:44,030
It makes it sink,
and it spreads it

100
00:07:44,063 --> 00:07:46,732
throughout
the water column and into the sediment.

101
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:49,302
And most of the water
column and the sediment

102
00:07:49,335 --> 00:07:51,237
have been damaged or destroyed

103
00:07:51,270 --> 00:07:53,339
as far as aquatic
organisms are concerned

104
00:07:53,372 --> 00:07:54,874
because it's toxic.

105
00:07:54,907 --> 00:07:56,909
We lost the Gulf of Mexico

106
00:07:56,943 --> 00:07:58,911
as far as an ecosystem,

107
00:07:58,945 --> 00:08:01,080
as a productive ecosystem.

108
00:08:01,113 --> 00:08:03,483
We didn't lose
the Gulf of Mexico

109
00:08:03,516 --> 00:08:06,452
as a source
of fuel, fossil fuel.

110
00:08:06,486 --> 00:08:09,455
And that drilling
and production will continue,

111
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:14,894
even though
the ecosystem has been destroyed.

112
00:08:14,927 --> 00:08:16,863
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
What I was learning in the Gulf

113
00:08:16,896 --> 00:08:19,932
was that no matter
how huge the catastrophe was,

114
00:08:19,999 --> 00:08:22,201
what really mattered was
who was telling the story.

115
00:08:22,235 --> 00:08:25,738
Let's go catch the sunset,
guys, then we'll come back in and check.

116
00:08:25,771 --> 00:08:28,741
You know, if I get sick
in 20 years, so be it,

117
00:08:28,774 --> 00:08:31,677
but my kids' bodies
are still developing.

118
00:08:31,711 --> 00:08:34,180
They say, "Oh, well,
everything's fine,

119
00:08:34,213 --> 00:08:36,682
"but stay inside your house
and keep your doors closed

120
00:08:36,716 --> 00:08:39,352
and your air conditioner
on recirculation."

121
00:08:41,020 --> 00:08:43,789
You know, I was taught not to throw
so much as a Coke can in the Bayou.

122
00:08:43,823 --> 00:08:45,291
This is our home.

123
00:08:45,324 --> 00:08:47,793
This is where we eat,
sleep, live.

124
00:08:47,827 --> 00:08:49,562
This is us. We're Bayou people.

125
00:08:49,595 --> 00:08:52,598
People don't understand
something. This isn't just about an income.

126
00:08:52,632 --> 00:08:56,135
This is about an entire way
of life in its entirety.

127
00:08:56,168 --> 00:08:58,604
We'll go out here and catch
150 pounds of shrimp,

128
00:08:58,638 --> 00:09:00,873
or go craw fishing
in the ditches or whatever,

129
00:09:00,907 --> 00:09:02,942
a couple of hundred
pounds of craw fish.

130
00:09:02,975 --> 00:09:05,912
5 or 6 families will get
together, no alcohol,

131
00:09:05,945 --> 00:09:08,314
boil seafood, barbecue whatever,

132
00:09:08,347 --> 00:09:10,750
and we have family time.

133
00:09:10,783 --> 00:09:13,753
You know, without that there,
I mean, yeah,

134
00:09:13,786 --> 00:09:16,455
we could cook other food,
but what about going in the bayou

135
00:09:16,489 --> 00:09:18,991
and going in the pirogue with
the kids, with no video games,

136
00:09:19,025 --> 00:09:21,427
no TV, no nothing?

137
00:09:21,460 --> 00:09:24,964
One on one, some people go
into the mountains behind their house,

138
00:09:24,997 --> 00:09:28,467
and they become one with nature.

139
00:09:28,501 --> 00:09:30,970
That's the bayou for us.

140
00:09:31,003 --> 00:09:33,973
If it's not there, what's
the point of being here?

141
00:09:34,006 --> 00:09:36,442
We're going to have
a dead fishery, contaminated land,

142
00:09:36,475 --> 00:09:39,412
a bag full of bills,
and a court date when this...

143
00:09:39,445 --> 00:09:44,550
when the federal government tells BP
that their cleanup has been completed.

144
00:09:44,584 --> 00:09:46,519
Why stay?

145
00:09:46,552 --> 00:09:48,955
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
That's when it hit me

146
00:09:48,988 --> 00:09:53,893
how much of this whole culture
was going to have to move.

147
00:10:02,234 --> 00:10:06,973
When I got home from the Gulf,
there was a new surprise neighbor.

148
00:10:10,109 --> 00:10:12,511
The Delaware River
Basin Commission

149
00:10:12,545 --> 00:10:15,314
was debating a new plan
to open up the river basin

150
00:10:15,348 --> 00:10:18,117
to 18,000 gas wells.

151
00:10:18,150 --> 00:10:20,886
The Commission had approved

152
00:10:20,920 --> 00:10:23,689
15 exploratory wells,

153
00:10:23,723 --> 00:10:26,459
and one was about a mile
from my house.

154
00:10:26,492 --> 00:10:28,361
Wait. Stop.

155
00:10:28,394 --> 00:10:30,663
I really want to start
at the middle,

156
00:10:30,696 --> 00:10:34,166
but I got to start
at the beginning.

157
00:10:34,200 --> 00:10:36,502
My parents built our house
in the Upper Delaware

158
00:10:36,535 --> 00:10:39,839
in the same year
I was born, 1972.

159
00:10:39,872 --> 00:10:43,876
It was my father's dream,
and my mom filled it with furniture.

160
00:10:43,909 --> 00:10:46,879
He told my mother, "I want
to build a house of love."

161
00:10:46,912 --> 00:10:49,448
I want to build a house
of love for you."

162
00:10:49,482 --> 00:10:52,551
He ended up building it
out of a $2.00 diagram

163
00:10:52,585 --> 00:10:54,787
out of "Popular Mechanics."

164
00:10:54,820 --> 00:10:56,756
For my father...

165
00:10:56,789 --> 00:11:00,660
a Holocaust survivor born
in Russia, fleeing the Nazis;

166
00:11:00,693 --> 00:11:05,598
and for my mother, the child of a poor Italian
immigrant family from New York City...

167
00:11:05,631 --> 00:11:09,168
on 19.5 acres, just a mile
from the Delaware,

168
00:11:09,201 --> 00:11:12,238
home was in the right place,

169
00:11:12,271 --> 00:11:14,774
one of those place
that maybe you might say,

170
00:11:14,807 --> 00:11:16,976
"Nothing ever happens."

171
00:11:17,009 --> 00:11:18,944
But then, in 2008,

172
00:11:18,978 --> 00:11:21,247
just like most people
in the Upper Delaware,

173
00:11:21,280 --> 00:11:22,748
we got a letter in the mail.

174
00:11:22,782 --> 00:11:24,717
We learned that our land was
on top of a formation

175
00:11:24,750 --> 00:11:27,219
called the Marcellus Shale,
and that the Marcellus Shale

176
00:11:27,253 --> 00:11:29,722
was the "Saudi Arabia"
of natural gas.

177
00:11:29,755 --> 00:11:32,158
We could lease our land
to the natural gas companies.

178
00:11:32,191 --> 00:11:35,161
We would receive a signing bonus
in the neighborhood of $100,000

179
00:11:35,194 --> 00:11:38,097
and untold thousands more
if we only let them...

180
00:11:38,130 --> 00:11:39,532
well...

181
00:11:39,565 --> 00:11:42,568
for the first time,
we heard that word.

182
00:11:42,601 --> 00:11:45,104
You know the word.
It's just like it sounds.

183
00:11:45,137 --> 00:11:48,040
If we only let them "Frack us."

184
00:11:48,074 --> 00:11:49,075
Fracking.
Fracking.

185
00:11:49,108 --> 00:11:50,209
Fracking.
Fracking them.

186
00:11:50,242 --> 00:11:52,111
The hydraulic
fracturing, or "fracking"...

187
00:11:52,144 --> 00:11:53,512
fracking...
fracking.

188
00:11:53,546 --> 00:11:54,714
So-called fracking...
fracking...

189
00:11:54,747 --> 00:11:55,848
Fracking... fracking.

190
00:11:55,881 --> 00:11:57,116
The Marcellus.
MAN: Shale gas.

191
00:11:57,149 --> 00:11:59,618
The shale.
[Male newscaster speaks German]

192
00:11:59,652 --> 00:12:01,253
Das Marcellus Shale.

193
00:12:01,287 --> 00:12:02,722
[Speaks German]
fracking.

194
00:12:02,755 --> 00:12:05,191
FOX, VOICE-OVER: The "F" word
isn't in the dark anymore.

195
00:12:05,224 --> 00:12:06,792
It's an outright hit.

196
00:12:06,826 --> 00:12:10,329
"Fracking" was Number 3 on
the list of most popular words

197
00:12:10,362 --> 00:12:12,798
in the English language in 2011,

198
00:12:12,832 --> 00:12:16,268
right behind "occupy"
and "deficit."

199
00:12:16,302 --> 00:12:20,306
And with one to two million
new wells projected,

200
00:12:20,339 --> 00:12:23,409
America is in a fracking frenzy.

201
00:12:23,442 --> 00:12:26,946
Hydraulic fracturing, or "fracking,"
is a method of gas extraction

202
00:12:26,979 --> 00:12:30,449
drilling deep down thousands
of feet to a shale formation

203
00:12:30,483 --> 00:12:33,619
and then forcing down the well
millions of gallons of water

204
00:12:33,652 --> 00:12:36,255
laced with toxic chemicals
at such intense pressures

205
00:12:36,288 --> 00:12:40,493
that it created fractures
in the rock and freed up the gas.

206
00:12:40,526 --> 00:12:43,028
But you never just drill
one well in a shale play,

207
00:12:43,095 --> 00:12:44,964
you drill thousands,

208
00:12:44,997 --> 00:12:49,001
creating an industrial
redefinition of the landscape.

209
00:12:49,034 --> 00:12:51,403
Millions of gallons
of water per well,

210
00:12:51,437 --> 00:12:54,440
thousands upon thousands
of truck trips,

211
00:12:54,507 --> 00:12:55,708
thousands of tons

212
00:12:55,741 --> 00:12:57,276
of proprietary chemicals

213
00:12:57,309 --> 00:12:59,411
injected into the ground.

214
00:12:59,445 --> 00:13:03,215
And because fracking explicitly is
exempt from the Safe Drinking Water Act,

215
00:13:03,249 --> 00:13:07,186
the industry doesn't have to tell the
public what chemicals they're using.

216
00:13:07,219 --> 00:13:10,556
The bigger picture still is
that we were just in the corner

217
00:13:10,623 --> 00:13:13,425
of the largest domestic
natural gas drilling campaign

218
00:13:13,459 --> 00:13:16,896
in history, now occupying
34 states.

219
00:13:16,929 --> 00:13:19,064
The gas drilling
and fracking industry

220
00:13:19,098 --> 00:13:22,168
was knocking on
the doors of millions.

221
00:13:22,201 --> 00:13:24,904
And with thousands of cases
of water contamination,

222
00:13:24,937 --> 00:13:26,872
air pollution,
and health problems

223
00:13:26,906 --> 00:13:28,607
reported across the U.S.,

224
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:31,644
it's not just the numbers
that get you dizzy.

225
00:13:31,677 --> 00:13:33,546
There was only one problem.

226
00:13:33,579 --> 00:13:35,548
The gas industry
denied everything.

227
00:13:35,581 --> 00:13:37,550
To date, we have found
no verified instance

228
00:13:37,583 --> 00:13:39,685
of hydraulic fracturing
harming groundwater.

229
00:13:39,718 --> 00:13:42,588
FOX, VOICE-OVER: The war for who
was going to tell this story

230
00:13:42,621 --> 00:13:44,957
was on.

231
00:13:55,634 --> 00:13:57,603
WOMAN, ON PHONE:
We had good water.

232
00:13:57,636 --> 00:14:00,506
The people in Dimock
don't have good water anymore.

233
00:14:00,539 --> 00:14:02,041
[Ticking]

234
00:14:02,074 --> 00:14:04,343
LESLEY STAHL, VOICE-OVER:
In the shale gas gold rush,

235
00:14:04,376 --> 00:14:06,612
Dimock is the ghost town.

236
00:14:09,949 --> 00:14:13,552
STAHL: How many of you lost
your water supply?

237
00:14:16,455 --> 00:14:18,824
MAN, VOICE-OVER: They said, "Dad,
we got gas in the water over there.

238
00:14:18,858 --> 00:14:21,227
I can actually shake
the jug up and light it."

239
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:24,763
You put a match
to your water and it went up in flames?

240
00:14:24,797 --> 00:14:27,800
I can take my water,
shake it up, turn it up,

241
00:14:27,833 --> 00:14:29,935
and it will explode-like.

242
00:14:38,010 --> 00:14:39,445
Scary?

243
00:14:39,478 --> 00:14:42,081
FEMALE NEWS ANCHOR:
All Cabot representatives say

244
00:14:42,114 --> 00:14:45,784
they don't believe drilling
operations caused the water problems.

245
00:14:50,489 --> 00:14:52,458
WOMAN: We're not
greedy people.

246
00:14:52,491 --> 00:14:54,193
We just want some
justice for something

247
00:14:54,226 --> 00:14:56,795
that's terribly wrong
that happened here.

248
00:14:59,999 --> 00:15:02,301
[Equipment beeping]

249
00:15:02,334 --> 00:15:04,637
[Engines chugging]

250
00:15:10,376 --> 00:15:13,512
GIRL: They look like
the Rovers on Mars.

251
00:15:25,090 --> 00:15:29,094
WOMAN, ON PHONE: Cabot said that they were not
responsible for the contamination of the wells.

252
00:15:29,128 --> 00:15:34,133
It is a scary situation
to accuse a large corporation

253
00:15:34,166 --> 00:15:36,101
of anything like that.

254
00:15:36,135 --> 00:15:39,605
FOX, VOICE-OVER: After years of trying to
negotiate with Cabot, the drilling company,

255
00:15:39,638 --> 00:15:42,541
the Dimock families
bound together to sue.

256
00:15:42,574 --> 00:15:45,544
When the lawsuit broke,
so did their silence.

257
00:15:45,577 --> 00:15:49,615
Bill Ely lit his water on fire
on every channel on television.

258
00:15:49,648 --> 00:15:51,884
And Sheila Ely, his wife,

259
00:15:51,917 --> 00:15:54,053
the mysterious voice
on the phone,

260
00:15:54,086 --> 00:15:56,889
invited me over to look at some
of her documentation.

261
00:15:56,922 --> 00:15:59,258
I like my pictures on the wall.

262
00:15:59,291 --> 00:16:01,660
When you have frames, you can't

263
00:16:01,694 --> 00:16:04,363
get all the pictures
up that you want.

264
00:16:04,396 --> 00:16:05,631
FOX: Uh-huh.

265
00:16:05,664 --> 00:16:07,866
So I just laminate,

266
00:16:07,900 --> 00:16:11,403
and I just keep
laminating and laminating.

267
00:16:11,437 --> 00:16:12,905
I have a laminator.

268
00:16:12,938 --> 00:16:14,273
BILL ELY: My ancestors
settled this spot

269
00:16:14,306 --> 00:16:16,008
right here, back in the 1800s.

270
00:16:16,041 --> 00:16:18,510
I'm, like,
fifth generation, and I hope there's

271
00:16:18,544 --> 00:16:20,279
5 more generations
after me that live here.

272
00:16:20,312 --> 00:16:22,481
And I'm not selling.
I'm not leaving.

273
00:16:22,514 --> 00:16:24,450
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
Just across the road, their nephew,

274
00:16:24,483 --> 00:16:26,185
Scott Ely, had worked for Cabot.

275
00:16:26,218 --> 00:16:28,754
Now he was the key witness
in their lawsuit.

276
00:16:28,787 --> 00:16:30,556
Imagine working for a company

277
00:16:30,589 --> 00:16:33,158
that destroyed
your family's water...

278
00:16:33,192 --> 00:16:36,028
We feel like horses being
pushed to a dirty hole.

279
00:16:36,061 --> 00:16:39,765
And, you know, horses won't drink
bad water. They just won't do it.

280
00:16:39,798 --> 00:16:42,801
FOX, VOICE-OVER: Or having to tell
your kids that they can't swim

281
00:16:42,835 --> 00:16:46,305
or fish in the creeks
and ponds you grew up in.

282
00:16:46,338 --> 00:16:48,273
I like fishing.
I like frog-catching.

283
00:16:48,307 --> 00:16:50,342
Me, too!
All I ever do for my life.

284
00:16:50,376 --> 00:16:52,311
Yeah, even when we go
in the pond,

285
00:16:52,344 --> 00:16:54,580
we try to catch fish,
we just get sick.

286
00:16:54,613 --> 00:16:56,515
Cabot should just deal
with us in the courtroom.

287
00:16:56,548 --> 00:17:00,252
They don't want to do that.
They want to street-fight all this.

288
00:17:00,285 --> 00:17:02,521
♪

289
00:17:02,554 --> 00:17:07,092
FOX, VOICE-OVER: The big, strong
Ely family was ready for a fight.

290
00:17:08,627 --> 00:17:11,430
Up and down Carter Road,
Craig and Julie Sautner and Ray Kemble

291
00:17:11,463 --> 00:17:13,599
had created a kind
of art installation

292
00:17:13,632 --> 00:17:16,101
of their well water
on their front lawns...

293
00:17:16,135 --> 00:17:18,937
All we want is to, you know,
have some kind of normalcy here.

294
00:17:18,971 --> 00:17:20,873
We want good water.
That's all we want.

295
00:17:20,906 --> 00:17:24,376
FOX, VOICE-OVER: And a kind of leader and
spokesperson emerged from the Dimock families.

296
00:17:24,410 --> 00:17:27,379
I've gone to
every congressman, representative,

297
00:17:27,413 --> 00:17:30,682
anyone who would listen:
DEP, Cabot, anyone I could think of.

298
00:17:30,716 --> 00:17:32,051
Begged for water from Cabot.

299
00:17:32,084 --> 00:17:34,486
All these people
begged... begged for water.

300
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:37,923
They told us there would be
one well out here, one well.

301
00:17:37,956 --> 00:17:41,360
And within the following year,
we have 30 wells now.

302
00:17:41,393 --> 00:17:44,530
I dread to imagine what's going to
happen to property value out here.

303
00:17:44,563 --> 00:17:48,167
How would you advertise this
house: "Bring your own water"?

304
00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:51,336
FOX, VOICE-OVER: There was so
much noise coming out of Dimock,

305
00:17:51,370 --> 00:17:54,540
it felt like the town was
standing in for the whole state.

306
00:17:54,573 --> 00:17:56,308
But Dimock wasn't alone.

307
00:17:56,341 --> 00:17:58,177
Over the past 4 years,

308
00:17:58,210 --> 00:18:01,480
a huge change had swept
across Pennsylvania.

309
00:18:01,513 --> 00:18:04,917
Governor Ed Rendell
had rolled out the red carpet

310
00:18:04,950 --> 00:18:06,985
for the gas drilling industry.

311
00:18:07,019 --> 00:18:10,456
Thousands of wells drilled...

312
00:18:10,489 --> 00:18:13,625
thousands of reported
violations.

313
00:18:15,494 --> 00:18:18,063
The "New York Times"
investigated and found that

314
00:18:18,097 --> 00:18:20,566
wastewater from drilling was
being inadequately treated

315
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:22,701
and dumped back
into water supplies

316
00:18:22,734 --> 00:18:24,736
all over Pennsylvania,

317
00:18:24,770 --> 00:18:27,239
and with this much evidence
bubbling up across the state,

318
00:18:27,272 --> 00:18:29,341
even the pro-drilling
Rendell administration

319
00:18:29,374 --> 00:18:31,376
had to take action.

320
00:18:31,410 --> 00:18:33,345
DEP issued violations to Cabot

321
00:18:33,378 --> 00:18:36,181
and stopped them from drilling
in a 9-square-mile radius,

322
00:18:36,215 --> 00:18:39,218
but no permanent solution
for residents' water contamination

323
00:18:39,251 --> 00:18:40,652
had been proposed.

324
00:18:40,686 --> 00:18:44,656
What the Dimock families
really wanted was permanent public water,

325
00:18:44,690 --> 00:18:48,193
and someone who could
make it happen finally showed up to listen.

326
00:18:49,595 --> 00:18:51,396
MAN, VOICE-OVER: Lance Simmens.

327
00:18:51,430 --> 00:18:54,233
I was special assistant
to Governor Ed Rendell

328
00:18:54,266 --> 00:18:56,235
for Intergovernmental Affairs.

329
00:18:56,268 --> 00:18:58,170
My primary responsibility

330
00:18:58,203 --> 00:19:01,206
was to make sure
that the Governor knew, on the ground,

331
00:19:01,240 --> 00:19:03,208
what was going on
in local communities.

332
00:19:03,242 --> 00:19:07,646
There was something obviously
drastically wrong with this picture.

333
00:19:07,679 --> 00:19:10,282
It's like, you know,
3 apples and a nail.

334
00:19:10,315 --> 00:19:13,285
And I said point-blank
to the Governor,

335
00:19:13,318 --> 00:19:16,288
who was sitting
within about 18 inches

336
00:19:16,321 --> 00:19:19,758
from me in a meeting
one day, I said,

337
00:19:19,791 --> 00:19:24,263
"We have got to get the people
of Dimock clean water.

338
00:19:24,296 --> 00:19:28,800
"This is the United States
of America, and we need to have this

339
00:19:28,834 --> 00:19:33,305
as a primary right for all
of our citizens."

340
00:19:33,338 --> 00:19:37,676
He agreed and he asked me
what we should do about it.

341
00:19:37,709 --> 00:19:40,712
And I said, "Let's connect

342
00:19:40,746 --> 00:19:43,715
to a public water supply."

343
00:19:43,749 --> 00:19:45,951
FOX, VOICE-OVER: After Lance
Simmens got to the governor,

344
00:19:45,984 --> 00:19:48,253
it felt like
a new day in Dimock.

345
00:19:48,287 --> 00:19:50,155
Pushed by a new policy,

346
00:19:50,189 --> 00:19:52,824
Department of Environmental
Protection Secretary John Hanger

347
00:19:52,858 --> 00:19:56,261
releases videotapes
of Dimock wells.

348
00:19:56,295 --> 00:19:59,598
We have video
of gas bubbling at those gas wells.

349
00:19:59,631 --> 00:20:02,134
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
The DEP revealed that Dimock wells

350
00:20:02,167 --> 00:20:05,304
had inadequate cement,
cracked cement, or no cement.

351
00:20:05,337 --> 00:20:07,606
The crucial part of the well
that's supposed to keep gas

352
00:20:07,639 --> 00:20:10,509
from migrating
into aquifers had failed,

353
00:20:10,542 --> 00:20:12,978
showing scientifically
that Cabot Oil & Gas

354
00:20:13,011 --> 00:20:15,881
had contaminated
Dimock's water with methane.

355
00:20:15,914 --> 00:20:18,450
[Drilling equipment clanging]

356
00:20:18,483 --> 00:20:22,487
But PA DEP had the videos
for a year and a half,

357
00:20:22,521 --> 00:20:25,090
so John Hanger, Secretary
of the Department, was in

358
00:20:25,123 --> 00:20:29,294
the uncomfortable position of calling his
own administration's policy inadequate,

359
00:20:29,328 --> 00:20:31,597
while at the same time
playing the hero.

360
00:20:31,630 --> 00:20:34,566
HANGER: We've had people
here in Pennsylvania

361
00:20:34,600 --> 00:20:39,471
without safe
drinking water for close to two years.

362
00:20:39,504 --> 00:20:43,208
That is totally,
totally unacceptable.

363
00:20:43,242 --> 00:20:45,544
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
The new policy was startling,

364
00:20:45,577 --> 00:20:47,579
although it was just
common sense.

365
00:20:47,613 --> 00:20:50,082
Pennsylvania would build
a water line to Dimock

366
00:20:50,115 --> 00:20:52,084
from Montrose, 7 miles away...

367
00:20:52,117 --> 00:20:53,986
the nearest municipal
water supply...

368
00:20:54,019 --> 00:20:56,588
and the state would sue
Cabot Oil & Gas

369
00:20:56,622 --> 00:20:59,725
for the cost... $12 million.

370
00:21:01,360 --> 00:21:05,297
Protestors in the crowd
lifted signs of other towns in Pennsylvania

371
00:21:05,330 --> 00:21:08,200
that had similar problems,
saying, "We, too, need a water line,"

372
00:21:08,233 --> 00:21:13,505
insisting that the Dimock
water line be a precedent for the state.

373
00:21:16,108 --> 00:21:20,178
Coming home from Dimock,
my own situation was escalating.

374
00:21:21,513 --> 00:21:24,316
The only place
they hadn't managed to drill

375
00:21:24,349 --> 00:21:27,352
in Pennsylvania was
the Delaware River Basin.

376
00:21:27,386 --> 00:21:29,855
It's the border
with New York State,

377
00:21:29,888 --> 00:21:33,492
and there are hundreds
of streams, tributaries

378
00:21:33,525 --> 00:21:36,061
to form that mighty river.

379
00:21:36,094 --> 00:21:38,430
15 million people get
their drinking water

380
00:21:38,463 --> 00:21:40,432
out of the Delaware
River Basin...

381
00:21:40,465 --> 00:21:43,835
New York City, Philadelphia,
and southern New Jersey.

382
00:21:43,869 --> 00:21:47,506
A lot depends on nothing
ever happening up here.

383
00:21:50,008 --> 00:21:51,943
There's an old adage:

384
00:21:51,977 --> 00:21:55,414
"You can't ever step in
the same stream twice."

385
00:21:55,447 --> 00:21:58,450
And from growing up running up and
down a trout stream connecting

386
00:21:58,483 --> 00:22:01,887
to the Delaware River, it's
fairly obvious how that's true.

387
00:22:01,920 --> 00:22:05,724
Every year, the snow melt
carves out a slightly new bank.

388
00:22:05,757 --> 00:22:08,927
Every year,
the spring thaw rushes in,

389
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:11,263
takes down a few trees.

390
00:22:11,296 --> 00:22:13,632
Every year, a new beach head,

391
00:22:13,665 --> 00:22:16,435
a place where a swimming hole
is slightly deeper.

392
00:22:16,468 --> 00:22:18,970
And, depending on the rainfall
and the weather,

393
00:22:19,004 --> 00:22:21,273
there could be
a rushing current,

394
00:22:21,306 --> 00:22:24,810
or a boulder revealed
by a drought that you've never seen before.

395
00:22:24,843 --> 00:22:30,315
But in this case,
something besides nature had changed this.

396
00:22:30,349 --> 00:22:32,417
Pro-drilling landowners
in my county

397
00:22:32,451 --> 00:22:34,353
had leased over 80,000 acres.

398
00:22:34,386 --> 00:22:38,390
The stream's always been my property
line, and now, just across from me,

399
00:22:38,423 --> 00:22:41,126
I could wake up and see off
my front porch every day

400
00:22:41,159 --> 00:22:44,663
the other side of the stream
was now leased.

401
00:22:44,696 --> 00:22:46,631
If drilling began,

402
00:22:46,665 --> 00:22:50,102
that side would be controlled
by the gas industry.

403
00:22:50,135 --> 00:22:53,105
Now it didn't matter
that my family never signed.

404
00:22:53,138 --> 00:22:56,274
I was completely surrounded,
and if they drilled,

405
00:22:56,308 --> 00:22:59,077
you'd never step in
the same stream again.

406
00:22:59,111 --> 00:23:02,347
The River Basin is controlled
by a 5-member body...

407
00:23:02,381 --> 00:23:05,016
4 governors of the states
that border the river

408
00:23:05,050 --> 00:23:07,586
and a representative
from the president...

409
00:23:07,619 --> 00:23:10,789
and New York State had
been paying attention to what was going on

410
00:23:10,822 --> 00:23:12,924
in Pennsylvania and
throughout the country.

411
00:23:12,958 --> 00:23:17,028
The New York legislature passed a one-year
moratorium on drilling throughout New York,

412
00:23:17,062 --> 00:23:19,197
and the federal government
was also taking a look.

413
00:23:19,231 --> 00:23:21,700
Prompted by Maurice Hinchey,
congressman from New York,

414
00:23:21,733 --> 00:23:25,203
the Federal Environmental
Protection Agency begins a two-year study

415
00:23:25,237 --> 00:23:27,706
of the effects of hydraulic
fracturing on groundwater,

416
00:23:27,739 --> 00:23:31,076
and EPA Administrator
Lisa Jackson declares

417
00:23:31,109 --> 00:23:34,846
that if states are falling
down on the job enforcing regulations,

418
00:23:34,880 --> 00:23:37,015
then the federal government
will step in.

419
00:23:37,048 --> 00:23:39,818
One such failed state
was Wyoming,

420
00:23:39,851 --> 00:23:43,355
and one such town was
a tiny little place called Pavillion.

421
00:23:43,388 --> 00:23:46,858
My backyard, New York,
and national policy tied

422
00:23:46,892 --> 00:23:49,628
to tiny little places
like Pavillion.

423
00:23:53,999 --> 00:23:56,168
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
EPA moved in and did

424
00:23:56,201 --> 00:23:58,804
a full groundwater study,
testing for hundreds of chemicals

425
00:23:58,837 --> 00:24:01,139
related to gas drilling
and the gas itself.

426
00:24:01,173 --> 00:24:03,308
MAN: This is the ultimate
detective novel.

427
00:24:03,341 --> 00:24:07,279
I mean, these people are
scientists and detectives

428
00:24:07,312 --> 00:24:10,782
and researchers,
and they are doing an extraordinary job,

429
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:14,820
but they are absolutely
moving mountains to get this done.

430
00:24:14,853 --> 00:24:19,224
FOX, VOICE-OVER: Most people
in the west don't own their mineral rights,

431
00:24:19,257 --> 00:24:23,428
so when the gas company showed up in
Pavillion, drilling over a hundred wells,

432
00:24:23,462 --> 00:24:26,631
landowners had no control
over where wells were drilled

433
00:24:26,665 --> 00:24:28,667
and no share of the revenue.

434
00:24:28,700 --> 00:24:33,104
FENTON: So, you know, they have all this
"Danger," you know, "No unauthorized personnel,"

435
00:24:33,138 --> 00:24:36,274
but it's in the middle
of my field. I have to...

436
00:24:36,308 --> 00:24:38,743
Now that we've got a big
oil field location

437
00:24:38,777 --> 00:24:41,246
in the middle of the field,
we have to irrigate around it.

438
00:24:41,279 --> 00:24:43,582
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
On August 31, 2010,

439
00:24:43,615 --> 00:24:46,318
the EPA released results
showing contamination

440
00:24:46,351 --> 00:24:48,386
in 19 out of
the water wells tested.

441
00:24:48,420 --> 00:24:50,856
Even though those chemicals
are in fracking fluids,

442
00:24:50,889 --> 00:24:54,893
Encana... the company doing the drilling...
denied responsibility,

443
00:24:54,926 --> 00:24:58,196
and Wyoming's governor was
openly hostile towards the EPA.

444
00:24:58,230 --> 00:25:01,233
Because of the gas industry's exemption
to the Safe Drinking Water Act,

445
00:25:01,266 --> 00:25:04,269
they're not required to report
which chemicals they're using.

446
00:25:04,302 --> 00:25:06,738
The investigation was ongoing,

447
00:25:06,771 --> 00:25:10,775
but EPA told Pavillion residents
not to drink their water.

448
00:25:10,809 --> 00:25:12,744
[Water running]

449
00:25:12,777 --> 00:25:15,580
Just down the road, Louis Meeks,
John Fenton's neighbor.

450
00:25:15,614 --> 00:25:17,582
Want a cold drink
of water? FOX: Yeah.

451
00:25:17,616 --> 00:25:20,085
FOX, VOICE-OVER:
His water still smelled like turpentine.

452
00:25:20,118 --> 00:25:22,621
This company come in,
right in the middle of our place,

453
00:25:22,654 --> 00:25:24,556
and we didn't do
nothing to them.

454
00:25:24,589 --> 00:25:27,259
It ain't no mansion, I know it ain't
no mansion, but it's home to us.

455
00:25:27,292 --> 00:25:29,261
We was happy here.
We have a garden.

456
00:25:29,294 --> 00:25:32,464
And we have fruit trees.
You know, there ain't much we need.

457
00:25:32,497 --> 00:25:37,469
Our kids were raised here. They rodeo'd
and everything else, you know, and, um...

458
00:25:37,502 --> 00:25:41,306
And this is the life
we wanted, but look at it now.

459
00:25:41,339 --> 00:25:43,341
You want me to shut my mouth?

460
00:25:43,375 --> 00:25:45,210
I'm not gonna.

461
00:25:45,243 --> 00:25:48,280
Do you want to see them letters I
wrote to the President? FOX: Sure.

462
00:25:48,313 --> 00:25:50,649
You know, I never was
a tree hugger or anything,

463
00:25:50,682 --> 00:25:53,018
but, you know, something
needs to be done.

464
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:54,986
I mean, you know,
this is terrible.

465
00:25:55,020 --> 00:25:57,455
FOX: And you only got
the letter in return from EPA?

466
00:25:57,489 --> 00:26:00,458
Yeah. In terms of EPA, don't you
